<div id="review_21060120" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/21060120" />
    <a title="Elise Russell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/984798-elise-russell"><img alt="Elise Russell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1391187024p2/984798.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/21060120?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elise Russell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elise Russell" href="/user/show/984798-elise-russell">Elise Russell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer21060120" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9166534705811985797">Interweaves the oral history &amp; 1st person narratives of the members of a N. Dakota town &amp; reservation to look at the aftermath &amp; effects of an isolated murder of a white family and subsequent lynching of several innocent Indians. I couldn&apos;t read this in one sitting, so I was finding myself having a hard time keeping all of the different threads and families straight. There seemed to be so many that by the end when a new one started, I couldn&apos;t help thinking, &quot;yikes, when is she is going to pull </span>
  <span id="freeText9166534705811985797" style="display:none">Interweaves the oral history &amp; 1st person narratives of the members of a N. Dakota town &amp; reservation to look at the aftermath &amp; effects of an isolated murder of a white family and subsequent lynching of several innocent Indians. I couldn't read this in one sitting, so I was finding myself having a hard time keeping all of the different threads and families straight. There seemed to be so many that by the end when a new one started, I couldn't help thinking, "yikes, when is she is going to pull all of this together?" She does, but I was still left scratching my head on a few things. Several of the storylines are incredible (Marn Wolde's &amp; Evelina Harp's were my favorites), but some of the others weren't compelling enough for me to really love the book as a whole.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9166534705811985797" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review21060120">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
