<div id="review_1904340272" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1904340272" />
    <a title="Jessie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45759846-jessie"><img alt="Jessie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531717590p2/45759846.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1904340272?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessie" href="/user/show/45759846-jessie">Jessie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1904340272" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1191614318974376253">You can’t beat Louise Erdrich for complex storylines, deeply human characters, and some degree of levity through the worst things that can happen, and The Plague of Doves is no exception. About a murder of a farming family on Ojibwe land in North Dakota, and the terrible hate crime that followed the initial slaying, this book follows families from both sides of the crimes, across generations, until certain resolutions are reached. This book explores secrets and shame, budding sexuality, changing</span>
  <span id="freeText1191614318974376253" style="display:none">You can’t beat Louise Erdrich for complex storylines, deeply human characters, and some degree of levity through the worst things that can happen, and The Plague of Doves is no exception. About a murder of a farming family on Ojibwe land in North Dakota, and the terrible hate crime that followed the initial slaying, this book follows families from both sides of the crimes, across generations, until certain resolutions are reached. This book explores secrets and shame, budding sexuality, changing political times, the death of small town America, racism and inequity, familial love, kidnappings, secrets, the “settlement” of the west, mental health, religious fervour, and so much more, all within a cast of characters that are so real, and in some cases so profoundly loveable. I adored this book. I couldn’t stop listening. I certainly couldn’t shut up about it. As always, I was blown away by the art of Erdrich. If you love a well narrated audiobook this one does it, if (and this is a big if), you can possibly tolerate the worst butchering of the pronunciation of “Louis Riel” these ears have ever heard, I’d recommend it in any format.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1191614318974376253" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


