    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_664949264" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/664949264" />
    <a title="Victor Carson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6344934-victor-carson"><img alt="Victor Carson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1350078135p2/6344934.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/664949264?book_show_action=true">Jul 11, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Victor Carson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Victor Carson" href="/user/show/6344934-victor-carson">Victor Carson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9780061556043" href="/book/show/2431590.The_Plague_of_Doves">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6344934-victor-carson?shelf=history-or-historical-fiction">history-or-historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer664949264" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1157552425531189347">I have now read five of Louis Erdrich’s novels, including her most recent best-seller, <i>The Round House</i>. I have liked all five but I think that <i>The Plague of Doves</i>, published in 2008 and nominated for a Pulitzer Prize in 2009, may be her best. As the Goodreads’ description says, <blockquote>“Louise Erdrich&apos;s … novel … centers on a compelling mystery. The unsolved murder of a farm family haunts the small, white, off-reservation town of Pluto, North Dakota. The vengeance exacted for this crime and the subseque</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText1157552425531189347" style="display:none">I have now read five of Louis Erdrich’s novels, including her most recent best-seller, <i>The Round House</i>. I have liked all five but I think that <i>The Plague of Doves</i>, published in 2008 and nominated for a Pulitzer Prize in 2009, may be her best. As the Goodreads’ description says, <blockquote>“Louise Erdrich's … novel … centers on a compelling mystery. The unsolved murder of a farm family haunts the small, white, off-reservation town of Pluto, North Dakota. The vengeance exacted for this crime and the subsequent distortions of truth transform the lives of Ojibwe living on the nearby reservation and shape the passions of both communities for the next generation. The descendants of Ojibwe and white intermarry, their lives intertwine; only the youngest generation, of mixed blood, remains unaware of the role the past continues to play in their lives.”</blockquote><br /><br />The craft with which this story is told makes this novel my favorite. The story shifts from narrator to narrator, some from the present, some from the recent past, and some from the very distant past, when the town of Pluto was founded. In fact, however, the story is not so much about the murder, which occurred in the early 1900’s, but about the interconnection of all the families associated with that event. Each of the characters is very thoroughly explored and it is that exploration that draws my admiration. The very old men and women who know the people who were involved in the murder think they know the truth about the event. At the very end of the novel, however, be prepared for a stunning revelation. Also, do not let your attention wander as you read. Characters and their descendents reappear as the various narrators take up the thread. I was sorry that I was not able to use Kindle’s XRay feature to keep track of the names – I listened to the Audiobook edition, but I hope to borrow the Kindle edition from the library shortly.<br /><br />The author’s knowledge of Indian culture and history shows to great advantage in <i>The Plague of Doves</i>. I look forward to reading more of her older and newer novels.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1157552425531189347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


